The grease covered contraption before you contains the necessary tools, clamps, cutter, vials and other assorted bits needed to use the tinkering skill. A tinkerer tool is needed to activate and use parts of the set.
Hearty billows fan the forge-borne flames. The air is blisteringly hot, leaving you feel light-headed and not quite yourself.
This sturdy blacksmith's anvil bears the dented sheen of long use. Something in you wonders what great weapons and armor have been shaped upon its well-worn surface.

The young tinkerer has many interesting devices that they can build, along with their base wires, widgets and gears. Some of these devices are even useful!

Gnomish Fire Stick - Using the drawing below, construct an enclosure for the Flaming Alchemy pack using 2 copper wires. Be certain to not build this device around an open flame.

Tinkered Mining Helmet - Protects and is functional! Using a crafted copper open helmet as a base, attach an Electrical Alchemy pack. Use 2 copper wires for controlling the device, as indicated...traditionally, the light is activated with a chin switch.

Gnomish Stun Rod - Useful for temporarily disabling brigands that you may meet on the road. Using the widget for the body of the device, carefully attach the Electrical Alchemy pack with 2 copper control wires. DO NOT POINT THE DEVICE AT YOURSELF DURING CONSTRUCTION. Doing so may lead to injury.

As you flip through the pages of this book, you see the properties of seven different types of gems.  How to capture these properties to cut, form, and polish.

Gems
--------------

*Malachite*
Malachite is a famous and very popular semi-precious stone. It is named for the green herb "mallow". Its banded light and dark green designs are one-of-a-kind, and give it a unique ornamental quality unlike that of any other stone.

Malachite, when cut properly, harnesses the power of Strength.
----------------------------------------------------------
*Amethyst*

Amethyst is the purple variety of quartz and is a popular gemstone. If it were not for its widespread availability, amethyst would be very expensive. The name "amethyst" means "not drunken." This was maybe due to a belief that amethyst would ward off the effects of alcohol, but most likely the name is referring to the almost wine-like color of some stones that they may have encountered. Its color is unparalleled, and even other, more expensive purple gemstones are often compared to its color and beauty. Although it must always be purple to be amethyst, it can and does have a wide range of purple shades. 

Amethyst, when cut properly, harnesses the power of Charisma.
----------------------------------------------------------
*Lapis Lazuli*

The ancient city of Ur has a thriving trade in lapis. The name is international, from the Latin, lapis, which means stone, and from the Arabic, azul, which means blue. Originally lapis was called ultramarinum, which means beyond the sea. Ground lapis was the secret of the blue in ultramarine, the pigment that painters use to paint the sea and the sky. Lapis is also popular in inlays.

Lapis Lazuli, when cut properly, harnesses the power of Dexterity.
----------------------------------------------------------
*Turquoise*

Turquoise is a valuable mineral and is possibly the most valuable, non-transparent mineral in the jewelry trade. It has been mined for eons. Its history also includes beautiful ornamental creations by Dwarves and Elves. Its popularity is still quite strong today.

Turquoise, when cut properly, harnesses the power of Constitution.
----------------------------------------------------------
*Opal*

In Precious Opal, the variety used most often in jewelry, there are many organized pockets of the spheres. These pockets contain spheres of approximately equal size and have a regular concentration, or structure, of the spheres. This has the effect of diffracting light at various wavelengths, creating colors. Each pocket produces a different color, with a different intensity depending on the angle from which a viewer sees it. The multicolored flashes of light that Opal emits gives it a truly beautiful and valuable look. 

Opal, when cut properly, harnesses the power of Wisdom and Save vs. Will but reduces the Strength of the wearer.  Due to it's natural properties, only Good and Neutral alignments can work and use this gem.
----------------------------------------------------------
*Onyx*

Onyx is the "Dark" sister of the Opal and can only be cut and used by Evil and Neutral aligned persons.

Onyx, when cut properly, harnesses the power of Dexerity and Save vs. Reflex but reduces the Strength of the wearer. 
----------------------------------------------------------
*Jade*

The toughness of jade is remarkable. It has a strength greater than steel and is sometimes put to work for axes, knives and weapons. Today, jade has become a symbolic stone used in ornaments and other religious artifacts. 

Jade, when cut properly, harnesses the power of Intelligence.
----------------------------------------------------------

Volume 2 contains recipes for the next set of gems.
This is a volume 1 of the Properties of Gems.

As you flip through the pages of this book, you see the properties of seven different types of gems.  How to capture these properties to cut, form, and polish.

Gems
--------------

*Pearl*

Pearls are an organic gem, created when an oyster covers a foreign object with beautiful layers of nacre. These organic gems can be found in ancient rock near oceans or within living oysters.

Pearl, when cut properly, harnesses the power of Wisdom.
----------------------------------------------------------
*Sapphire/Black Sapphire*

The Sapphires are the second hardest natural mineral known.  The Black variety of Sapphire is more rare than the blue variety.

Sapphire, when cut properly, enhances the power of Wisdom, Save vs. Negative Energy, but cuts the Constitution of the bearer.  Due to it's natural properties, only Good aligned characters can cut and wear this gem.

Black Sapphire, when cut properly, enhances the power of Dexterity, Save vs. Positive Energy, but reduces the Charisma of the bearer.  Due to it's natural properties, only Evil aligned characters can cut and wear this gem.
----------------------------------------------------------
*Fire Opal*

Fire opal breaks all the rules for opal. Opal is a gem valued for its play of color, the shifting light showing through from its depths. Body color is only a backdrop for the main attraction. But the color of fire opal is hard to ignore: hot yellows, oranges, and reds so bright they look as though they might glow in the dark. 

Fire Opal, when cut properly, enhances the power of Charisma, Save vs. Fortitude, but reduces the Dexterity of the bearer.
----------------------------------------------------------
*Ruby*

Which colour would you spontaneously associate with love and vividness, passion and power? Obviously this will evoke the colour red. Red symbolizes love, it emanates warmth and a strong sense of life. Red is also the colour of Ruby, the King of gemstones. After all, in the fascinating realm of gemstones rubies are the generally accepted emperors.  Ruby is the red sister of the Sapphire.

Ruby, when cut properly, enhances the power of Constitution and Save vs. Mind.
----------------------------------------------------------
*Emerald*

Emeralds are fascinating gemstones. They show the most beautiful, deepest and most brilliant green imaginable: Emerald green. Inclusions are allowed, and nevertheless, in top qualities fine Emerald are even more valuable than diamonds.

Emerald, when cut properly, enhances the power of Dexterity and Save vs. Fear.
----------------------------------------------------------
*Diamond*

Diamond is the ultimate gemstone, having few weaknesses and many strengths. It is well known that Diamond is the hardest substance found in nature.
As a gemstone, Diamond's single flaw (perfect cleavage) is far outdistanced by the sum of its positive qualities. It has a broad color range, high refraction, high dispersion or fire, very low reactivity to chemicals, rarity, and of course, extreme hardness and durability. 
A skilled diamond setter and/or jeweler will prevent any of this single flaw from being in a position to be struck while mounted in a jewelry piece. 
----------------------------------------------------------

Favored by druids for its graceful and natural beauty, malachite is known for its strikingly ornamental bands of light and dark green that alternate throughout the entire stone. Painters have also been known to crush the gem and use it as a pigment. Adventurers have discovered that the gem bubbles and dissolves readily in acid, making it an effective - if expensive - means of identifying certain dangerous substances.

Basics of Tailoring
Tailoring will require harden hides from tanners. The harden hides are made into colored cloths if used with dyes by a tailor.

Dyes
-----
To make clothes you must first Dye Hides from animals. You can use the extracts from a variety of different flowers to make dye of all colors. 

Hides
-----
Hardened small, medium and large hides can be used in tailoring. You turn the hides into colored cloth using the appropriate dye and the tailors knife.

Cloth
-------
The final products of tailoring are all made with dyed cloths. Large cloths can be used to make clothes, cloaks, armor & bags. Medium cloths are used to make belts and bags. Gloves and boots can be made with small cloths.  Some items require one cloth and others two of the same color.
